    <section data-title="Comments" data-nosnippet="true">
        <div class="c-article-section" id="article-comments-section">
            <h2 class="c-article-section__title js-section-title js-c-reading-companion-sections-item" id="article-comments">Comments</h2>
            <div class="c-article-section__content" id="article-comments-content">
                <p class="c-article-section__content-banner">Commenting on this article is now closed.</p>
                <ol class="u-list-reset c-article-comments-list">
                    
                        <li id="comment-6287141947" class="c-article-comments-list__item">
                            
                                <p class="c-article-comments-list__submitted"><span class="c-article-comments-list__author">Giovanni Di Guardo</span> <time datetime="2023-09-27T08:26:57Z" class="c-article-comments-list__date">27 September 2023, 08:26</time></p>
                            
                            <p>Cortisol and "Long COVID", a lot of food for thoughts</p><p>Together with the marked differences characterizing their immune response profiles, your interesting article also reports lower cortisol levels in "Long COVID" (LC)-affected patients (1). Noteworthy, SARS-CoV-2 shows a high binding affinity to linoleic acid (LA), an essential free fatty acid, with this resulting in a diminished spike (S) protein interaction with the angiotensin-converting enzyme 2 (ACE2) viral receptor. Furthermore, LA supplementation synergizes with the antiviral drug remdesivir, thereby suppressing SARS-CoV-2 replication (2). Such an intriguing virus-LA interaction mechanism may also provide biological plausibility for the favourable outcomes seen in patients with severe COVID-19 disease forms, following corticosteroid (dexamethasone) administration. Natural and synthetic corticosteroids are known, in fact, to selectively inhibit the phospholipase-A2 enzyme, converting LA into linolenic acid, with this representing a critical step in the biosynthesis of prostaglandins and leukotrienes, both of which are key mediators in inflammatory reactions (3). <br>Consequently, based upon their lower cortisol levels (1), a reduced phosphospholipase-A2 inhibition could be reasonably expected to occur in LC-affected individuals, with this likely resulting in a stronger binding of the SARS-CoV-2 S protein to the ACE2 receptor molecule, ultimately leading to increased viral replication and persistence in LC-affected hosts' tissues.</p><p>References</p><p>1) Klein, J., Wood, J., Jaycox, J. et al. Distinguishing features of Long COVID identified through immune profiling. Nature (2023). <a href="https://doi.org/10.1038/s41586-023-06651-y" rel="nofollow noopener" target="_blank" title="https://doi.org/10.1038/s41586-023-06651-y">https://doi.org/10.1038/s41...</a>.</p><p>2) Toelzer, C., Gupta, K., Yadav, S.K.N. et al. Free fatty acid binding pocket in the locked structure of SARS-CoV-2 spike protein.Science 370,725-730(2020).DOI:10.1126/science.abd3255.</p><p>3) Robbins &amp; Kumar Basic Pathology, 11th Edition. Inflammation Chapter. Elsevier - Health Sciences Division (2022).</p><p>Giovanni Di Guardo, DVM, Dipl. ECVP,</p><p>Retired Professor of General Pathology and Veterinary Pathophysiology <br>at the Veterinary Medical Faculty of the University of Teramo, 64100 Teramo, Italy <br>Current address: Viale Pasteur, 77 - 00144 - EUR - Rome, Italy <br>(E-mail address: gdiguardo@unite.it; cellular phone no.: +39-347-6317862)</p>
                        </li>
                    
                        <li id="comment-6290913332" class="c-article-comments-list__item">
                            
                                <p class="c-article-comments-list__submitted"><span class="c-article-comments-list__author">elkewynberg</span> <time datetime="2023-10-02T11:38:09Z" class="c-article-comments-list__date">2 October 2023, 11:38</time></p>
                            
                            <p>It's a real shame this important paper is not available Open Access to ensure its results are available to all readers (long COVID patients, researchers/academics, clinicians) regardless of their ability to pay for access.</p>
                        </li>
                    
                </ol>
            </div>
        </div>
    </section>

            

        </div>
</article>
</main>

